### What problem does this feature solve?
Right now Vuex warns you (in dev mode) when changing the state from outside - which is good and important. But right now it can (accidentally) be circumvented with closures, by adding a function to the state.

```javascript
// Create a closure
const myFunctionFactory = () => {
	const myValues = {
		foo: 0,
	};

	return () => {
		myValues.foo  = 1;
		return myValues.foo;
	};
};

// Get the function inside the closure
const myFunction = myFunctionFactory();

// Add the function to the state
Vue.set( state, 'myFunction', myFunction );

// New each time the function is called, a different result is returned
state.myFunction(); // => 1;
state.myFunction(); // => 2;
state.myFunction(); // => 3;
state.myFunction(); // => 4;
```

This can introduce really subtle bugs and also makes time travel unusable. There also seems to be no way to prevent this, except for not allowing functions in state at all.

It would be great to hear other peoples opinions on the subject.

### What does the proposed API look like?
In my opinion adding functions to the state should be discouraged in docs.

In dev mode it would be great if an error could be thrown if a function is discovered in the state - at least if strict mode is enabled or something like that.

